<div id="review_3779301070" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3779301070" />
    <a title="Ariel Fiona" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/24666802-ariel-fiona"><img alt="Ariel Fiona" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1607710388p2/24666802.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3779301070?book_show_action=true">Jun 12, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ariel Fiona" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ariel Fiona" href="/user/show/24666802-ariel-fiona">Ariel Fiona</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/24666802-ariel-fiona?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/24666802-ariel-fiona?shelf=michael-swanwick">michael-swanwick</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3779301070" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9185641972845640964">This sure seems like a random collection of picaresque adventures but the way all the puzzle pieces actually come together is both subtle and breathtaking. Dragons of Babel is a complete standalone plotwise, and the main commonality with The Iron Dragon&apos;s Daughter is the bizarre industrialized faerie setting in which technological development happened in a magical world sidelong to our own. Having read the previous book will not help you grapple with the way things work in this one in the least,</span>
  <span id="freeText9185641972845640964" style="display:none">This sure seems like a random collection of picaresque adventures but the way all the puzzle pieces actually come together is both subtle and breathtaking. Dragons of Babel is a complete standalone plotwise, and the main commonality with The Iron Dragon's Daughter is the bizarre industrialized faerie setting in which technological development happened in a magical world sidelong to our own. Having read the previous book will not help you grapple with the way things work in this one in the least, because Swanwick paints a picture through imaginative and largely unexplained anecdotes and details that draw on folklore rather than by the logical systematized worldbuilding so common these days. If I had to describe the overall package I'd say it's a satirical post-9/11 antiwar fantasy that subverts both the secret king trope and the entire idea of monarchy. So, pretty much incomparable.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9185641972845640964" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


