    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3905317030" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3905317030" />
    <a title="Phairlever Pierson" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/77840583-phairlever-pierson"><img alt="Phairlever Pierson" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1518725503p2/77840583.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3905317030?book_show_action=true">Mar 23, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Phairlever Pierson" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Phairlever Pierson" href="/user/show/77840583-phairlever-pierson">Phairlever Pierson</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3905317030" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16677050672278532395">This is a novel that goes a lot of places and does a lot of things, but in the end it hasn&apos;t really gone anywhere or done anything significant. I guess you could call it a bildungsroman, but the protagonist doesn&apos;t change or evolve much. In fact, he is developed hardly at all. I felt virtually no connection to him. It&apos;s fun and creative at times, and the best thing I can say for it is that the names and places, the history, the creatures, and so on, somehow don&apos;t grate, which is a feat in itself</span>
  <span id="freeText16677050672278532395" style="display:none">This is a novel that goes a lot of places and does a lot of things, but in the end it hasn't really gone anywhere or done anything significant. I guess you could call it a bildungsroman, but the protagonist doesn't change or evolve much. In fact, he is developed hardly at all. I felt virtually no connection to him. It's fun and creative at times, and the best thing I can say for it is that the names and places, the history, the creatures, and so on, somehow don't grate, which is a feat in itself, because they are mostly inane, showoff-y, but still retain a lightness. I like Swanwick's style, but I don't think I laughed once, when I was supposed to. I chuckled maybe a few times. There are some nice nods to Tolkien and others, but I will have forgotten this novel in a matter of days. It's a romp without a narrative of any consequence. Two and a half stars. Mediocrity at its high point, which is the exact middle. </span>
  <a data-text-id="16677050672278532395" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


